  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Enfeoffment of the Grand Marquis of Dailing
  author: Choe Yugyeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I impart this edict to you:

    When a ruler enfeoffs his sons and brothers widely, establishing them as guardians of distant domains, it is not merely for affection's sake, nor to grant them wealth and honor. Rather, it is to exalt the ancestral temple and fortify the altar of the state. How much more so in your case—descended from the bonds of heaven itself, you stand as the hope of the royal lineage. Early you revealed the virtue of a mature man, and thus you deserve to receive the glory of being granted domain and title.

    Having considered the counsel of many, I now bestow upon you this gracious mandate. Respect and uphold its ordinances, and understand the depths of my sincere regard. I hereby dispatch my emissary, [Official Name], to conduct the ceremony of enfeoffment according to proper rites. Along with this, various gifts are granted to you, as detailed in the attached record.
  footnotes:
    - This is a royal edict of enfeoffment, a formal proclamation establishing a royal kinsman as a marquis with territorial authority.
    - The 'ancestral temple' and 'altar of the state' refer to the fundamental institutions of the kingdom that the ruler seeks to preserve through strategic allocation of power to trusted relatives.
    - The reference to 'bonds of heaven' (天倫) emphasizes the natural and cosmic order of familial relationships within the royal house.
